a:260:{i:0;a:1:{s:2:"id";s:19:"2390986958176356558";}i:1;a:1:{s:10:"short_code";s:11:"CEuffhwsYjO";}i:2;a:1:{s:12:"created_time";i:1599247878;}i:3;a:1:{s:7:"caption";s:2039:"#suicidepreventionmonth

You ever have those years (I like to call them “banner years”), where everything either goes really well or your entire world flips upside down?

2013 was my first banner year: I was diagnosed with generalized anxiety, developed an eating disorder and almost failed social studies and chemistry because I couldn’t motivate myself to do work. On top of that, a small cohort of my high school friends spread nasty rumours about me until I became severely depressed. This depression has followed me my entire life since. 

2016 was my second banner year: My dad passed away unexpectedly and my mom was diagnosed with breast cancer, this time in Stage 4. 

2019 was my third banner year: I went through (and recovered from) a horrible breakup, was verbally and sexually harassed by someone I trusted, lost touch with my friends and became even more body-dysmorphic.

The cynical parts of me look at this timeline and think “wow, every three years something really f***ed up happens in my life”. Whatever struggle I’m facing, whatever situation I’m dealing with — sometimes I just can’t look at the bright side. It’s an awful feeling and it can leave you helpless and hopeless. 

But it’s important to remain positive, when and if you can. In 2014 I got accepted into Mount Royal University and made an entirely new group of friends. In 2016 I travelled to Ireland with an amazing group of women during a travel abroad program. In 2018 I graduated university with a 4.0 GPA. In 2020, I wrote and recorded two original songs – and I got a puppy!

Anyways, what I’m trying to get at here is that you are SO much stronger than you know. I didn’t think I could make it through half of the crap life has thrown my way. But here I am, writing this blog in the hopes that I can inspire someone else to be strong.

You will have bad banner years…but you will also have good ones. The thing is to focus on the WHOLE picture. I know it’s difficult, but trust me, you got this♥️

